                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d45">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/158:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        American Delegate</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-22T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 22, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>488. Your 1019, March 21, 11 a.m. We hope it may be possible for the Committees
                    to proceed with the work in hand. Nevertheless, if at any time you become
                    convinced that as a result of the general political situation in Europe, no
                    useful purpose can be served by continuing to proceed with negotiations, you are
                    authorized in your discretion to acquiesce in but not to propose an
                    adjournment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
